    <statement><p>Add or subtract the rational expressions to a single rational expression and then simplify. If applicable, state the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{1}{x-2}-\frac{4}{x^{2}-4}} =}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{1}{x+2}, x\ne 2</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{1}{x-2}-\frac{4}{x^{2}-4}} 
      \amp = {\frac{1}{x-2}}-\frac{4}{(x - 2)(x + 2)} \\
      \amp = \frac{1\cdot({x+2})}{({x-2})\cdot({x+2})} -\frac{4}{(x - 2)(x + 2)} \\
      \amp = \frac{{x+2-4}}{(x - 2)(x + 2)} \\
      \amp = \frac{{x-2}}{(x - 2)(x + 2)} \\
      \amp = {\frac{1}{x+2}, x\ne 2}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>{x-2}</m> was canceled, the domain condition lost during the simplification is <m>x \ne {2}</m>.</p>
</solution>
